node.text: Your 9-5 is simply a temporary income source to allow you to buy assets in order to replace it with passive income.

Credit is NOT a great measure of wealth.

You can have an 850 credit score and STILL be broke. You can also have a 0 credit score and have an $850k net worth. 

It’s good to have credit, but your net worth is a better number to focus on.
Your income alone *DOES NOT* determine wealth. Your spending habits do.

node.text:
I get the “you only live once” message in response to almost every single one of my post, which i totally agree with but for a different reason then the people using it as an excuses to recklessly spend money.. 

Life is short, so why not spend a few years aggressively buying assets and getting your money situated so that you can have the leverage to live the rest of your life on your own terms? 

More money = more options. More debt = less options. 

Balance is key at the end of the day. You can enjoy your life AND build wealth at the same time. Just make sure you’re not “enjoying your life” at the expense of your financial future. That’s all.

Long-term investors with long-term goals win.

Short-term investors expecting instant results lose.

Buying a home cost more than just the down payment! 

Many new home buyers forget to calculate the additional cost of buying a home and end up with surprises as they go through the home buying process. 

I hope this post helps those who are preparing to buy a home soon avoid any surprises.

Keep in mind these are just general estimates. There may be additional (or less) home buying cost in your specific market. 

It’s always good to have some extra cash to cover any additional inspections or repairs that might occur during the process as well. 💯
Love this 👏 It all comes down to consistency and patience at the end of the day!
